Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists from the University of California at Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to search among the stars related, that is, arising from one cluster.
The results of their research, the authors published in the journal Nature, and briefly with them can be found on the website of the University.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, which precedes the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster can lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulation conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to model two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
This object for several million years under the influence of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added marker paints to the original gas streams and found that the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical uniformity.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
