Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that protects trade union organization as a civil right.
“Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Progressive Faction Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to introduce the Workers’ Empowerment Act along with the civil rights symbol John Lewis.
This ground-breaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunities to discriminate against trade union organizations as it does against other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of anti-trade union opponents.
Amending the Labor Relations Regulation Act to allow workers facing discrimination for union membership to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and penalties - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to remember a very American idea.
Despite the attacks that unions have suffered in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans once supported countries around the world to adopt, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions played a role in the formation of the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight D. Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognising that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations in order to protect and improve the working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal effect; measures aimed at this end will be found to be unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and to have that trade union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — should be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as it should.
The official recognition of labor rights as human rights – and the expansion of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against union organization – is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Close All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana
In the US, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the implementation of the Louisiana law, which his supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginal in June and was due to go into effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have hospital admission authority within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that for the time being, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while still seeking such authority.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to seek power,” Judge John DeGravells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which time the judge will render a more permanent decision on this law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to get hospital powers.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women are protected from the insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision concerned doctors from the two clinics who had not acted as plaintiffs in the case and had also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently found such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say the admissions laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, according to the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission powers await a decision.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas for domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of product in the range of retail chains should be of Russian production, said the deputy of the state Duma from the faction "Fair Russia" Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper "Izvestia".
The document will be further detailed in order to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. <0x3C>...> For the other groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers," Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the basis of state regulation of trade activities in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea to introduce a 50% quota in retail chains is included in the package of incentive measures for Russian manufacturers.
There will be several times more domestic goods on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to Sergey Litvinenko, a lawyer of Nalogovik, a member of the independent expert center Public Duma, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive and will lead to growth.
The plus will be farmers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian producers will be able to increase the volume of their activities and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will develop faster, will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately," the expert said.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not make it to the shelves of local stores due to high competition from foreign analogues.
Now, after the imposition of the embargo, this niche has been freed and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now is the "moment of calm" when the old players have already left, and the new ones have not yet come.
After almost a month, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the growth of prices for finished products," Tamara Kasyanova, First Vice-President of the All-Russian Public Organization Russian Club of Financial Directors, PhD, told AIF.ru.
Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will make it possible to consolidate the sector behind local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper at the expense of subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will unfold between companies working under the uniform laws of the industry.
On the other hand, notes Kasyanova, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots is not in all respects.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to "catch up" the share of Russian goods to half the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that poor-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of manufactured in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied," the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in this situation, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was again talked about by economists in February this year due to the continued devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers in the formation of orders to suppliers to take into account domestic manufacturers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently along the path of import substitution, and the system of production planning for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter period of time,” said Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, such as the dairy sector, where imports accounted for 25 per cent.
Our farmers are really able to completely cover the counters of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can also receive a powerful impetus.
As you know, the largest share of imports is kept for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still Russian products," Kasyanova says.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, since this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that full-fledged import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be made.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide”, – the expert notes.
Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who procreate in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
The researchers analyzed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the Institute for Medical Research QIMR Berghofer reported that those living in regions and remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
RELATED: New Drugs May Slow Down Lung and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers followed the women’s medical path for seven years.
Dr Jordan said the woman's age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, current illness and socioeconomic status also affected her chances of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that an untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly in the big cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of on-the-go services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and programs to support people undergoing treatment away from their home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Neve, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
