Inflation has come out of vacation.
Will the Russians feel a sharp rise in prices?
As a result of cross-sanctions of Russia and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the forecasts of the authorities, VTB Capital analysts are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year even less - 6.5%.
However, according to the newspaper Kommersant, this week the MAYOR should make “small but fundamental” adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency can reduce the estimate of inflation for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth of incomes.
The forecast assumed that food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How could such high inflation be expected?
The current situation implies a one-time shock, but the downward trend in inflation will not change," the source said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the government’s financial and economic bloc regarding inflation and predict a price increase of 8% in 2014.
The main effect of product bans will come along with the possible introduction of a sales tax (SST) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
The inflation peak of 9% will be in February, after which the annual growth rate of prices will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation introduced “accurate sanctions”.
AIF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of Analytical Department of AForex FC:
The increase in prices is already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially important products became more expensive, the government was forced to launch measures to systematically monitor price stability in order to prevent the risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting to regulators on a daily basis so that authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason triggers price increases.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the enormous rate of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian megaregulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as the embargo on the import of food products from countries that joined the sanctions against Russia.
Had inflationary pressures remained under control, the value of the basket of the minimum set of products would not have jumped by 12% in a quarter alone.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final value.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the mechanism of import substitution, as well as to increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, the retaliatory sanctions will continue to bear the risks of increasing the inflationary component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorating prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvaev, Director of the Analytical Department of Alpari
In the 90s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in zero it was also above the current level, another thing that was then compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think by the end of the year, inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, asset manager of the Maguta Fund
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is still successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, first of all, on the financial sector - this can lead to certain difficulties and increase inflationary expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in the purchase of cash currency in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the gradual weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and state regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer lull and, perhaps, this autumn will become more tangible.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, as the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Gardening centers are saddened by the decline in the number of homeowners
Such a drop, driven by an exceptional decline in the number of homeowners under 35, could result in horticultural centres losing tens of millions of pounds a year when today’s young consumers reach the “basic age of horticulture,” according to a HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, people who rent a home spend an average of 55 percent of the amount that homeowners spend on gardening.
It mentions the increase in the number of people living in highly urban areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting yards in front of a house for parking and the reduction in the size of the garden as other factors threatening the industry, whose annual sales are estimated to be <0xC2><0xA3>5 billion.
In Greater London, where the number of homeowners fell from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, the UK has the lowest level of spending on household goods for gardeners.
HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society have reported that renting housing and not having space for a garden does not mean people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief horticultural adviser at RHS, said: “Plant cultivation in containers, for example, is particularly popular with tenants who can transport plants with them when they move.”
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as the “golden age” of retailing for gardening goods as a result of the increasing number of homeowners and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
