China's largest companies join forces against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China’s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left behind even its American rivals – eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($ 814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% by each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said.
The company is scheduled to be registered in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu’s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, whose number of users is about 438 million people), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $ 8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea coast).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American network of cinemas AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, the development of which will be engaged in the creation of a competitor to Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, thanks to the merger, Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new site is set to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, Dong Tse said.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupon selling services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the largest pie in online commerce,” said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin.
“There is currently no real O2O site in China, and in this situation, the chances are approximately equal for everyone,” he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the world’s largest, and McKinsey & Co. estimates its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg: this is more than the population of any country in the world, except India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015 this number may grow to 850 million people.
Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was China’s richest man until recently, but according to the Bloomberg Millionaire Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his share in Alibaba.
Baidu CEO Robin Lee now ranks third among China’s richest people, while Wanda’s Wang Jianlin is fourth.
“This battle is very interesting to watch: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge an even richer one,” said Cao Lei, director of China’s e-commerce research center in Hangzhou.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: "Rome can not be built in one day."
The fact that with Alibaba it is not so easy to compete not only with new companies, but also with well-deserved leaders of world e-commerce, is evidenced by the report published yesterday on financial indicators of Alibaba for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as a cross between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit for the period is almost twice the same sum of competitors – it grew almost three times year-on-year and amounted to $ 1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has tremendous potential to generate money, thanks in large part to its mobile applications,” an analyst at Hong Kong’s Arete Research Service told Bloomberg.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the website of the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July amounted to 188 million, which significantly exceeds the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions for the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba has yet to disclose the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) can take place as early as September 16.
The company’s road show, which precedes this event, starts on September 3.
Alibaba’s IPO is expected to be a record in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise about $ 20 billion.
So far, the record for the amount of funds raised on US exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 held the initial placement of its shares, earning $17.9 billion.
