Chairman of the Expert Council, State Secretary, Deputy Head of the FAS Andrey Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it will turn out, as in the famous rerun of Arkady Raikin's "Atelier": "Is there a claim to the buttons?".
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and landmines rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory was recovering from fighting.
The start of school activities brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed traces of fragments from the walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
“We’re a little scared, but we’re looking forward with joy,” said Ronit Barth, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was “a little weird” to start going to school again.
“It was a difficult time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before the cease-fire agreement halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not take to the streets or left their homes, fleeing to safer areas further away from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a fragment of a Palestinian mine, doubt they should go back.
The education ministry said about a dozen families had still not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at the time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the Gaza border that has been badly damaged by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, "We will do everything possible to give you knowledge and ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire last Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas' demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to Palestinian and UN estimates.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and landmines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip were damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people took refuge in more than 100 schools, which were converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials last week postponed the start of the school year.
“I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza’s schools.
According to a popular criterion, real estate prices showed the largest winter growth in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic housing price index for the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
This increase led to a cumulative increase of 4.2 per cent in June, July and August, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
The annual price increase was 10.9 percent, more than double the 12 months to August 2013 growth, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
Tim Lawless, director of research at RP Data, said Sydney and Melbourne are leading the two-tier market.
RP Data figures show that in Sydney, house prices have risen 16.1 percent over the past year, while in Melbourne they have risen 11.7 percent.
The next most powerful markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose by an average of five to six percent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which saw government spending cuts, where prices rose just 1.4 percent year-on-year.
Mr Lawless said that now that spring had begun, there would be an increase in the number of properties put up for sale over the next few months, which would be a “real test” for the market.
“Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sale and the current conditions with a low interest rate, it is likely that the cost of housing will still rise over the next three months,” he said.
How people live in the oldest house of Ufa
In the former house of goldsmiths and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on the street October Revolution 57/1 (the former Great Kazan) 18 apartments.
The house of the XVIII century from the time of construction has not changed much, except for the dilapidation.
Outsiders come here as an excursion, and tenants suffer more than rejoice, from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is almost 300 years old.
Old courtyard, always open door, creaking stairs.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls are cracked, and in the gaps from the peeled plaster in some places the street is visible.
Everything seems to be based on an honest word.
And the locals say, "You don't think that's true."
Living in a wooden house of the XVIII century is very difficult, - says Tatiana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment number 3.
The object is under state protection, but money for its maintenance has not been allocated for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits, which the authorities have simply forgotten.
The last repair was 40 years ago.
The walls are still badly-poorly held, but the foundation is all rotten.
Many residents still go to the toilet on the street, and wash once a week in a public bath.
How can you be happy in such conditions?
The road goes right under the windows, even there is no pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only heard before: there is a stream of cars under the windows.
You see, the windows are shaking all the time, we can't open the windows, and we're used to the noise.
People get used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
We have two rooms and we live with our three children.
And for other families, the conditions are much worse, on the second floor in general, the ceilings are a little more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana offers to visit a neighbor from apartment No. 6 Lyudmila Starostina.
A nice hospitable woman from the threshold offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile says:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m2 for four people, and we live like this: we are with our husband and daughter and granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila surrounds the room with her eyes: mezzanines, two sofas with the letter "g"; on one of them there is a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very closely and not much different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But from the ceiling regularly flows: the plumbing system is not suitable anywhere.
Lyudmila talks about her apartment casually and amazingly at the same time, like an Italian woman whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it reduces into one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The plumbing was done about 40 years ago during the last repair.
Then they made us a small kitchen in a corner and a toilet from the former closet.
We live exactly where Demidov and his family lived, servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
In the real estate center Ufa say, privatization does not matter.
We still get only one-room apartment, we can not claim more.
Four months ago, they promised to resettle us, but it didn’t go beyond promises.
I'm not used to complaining, and I won't.
In this apartment (room!) lived a whole dynasty: my grandmother and grandfather, mom and dad, I with my husband and my daughter with my granddaughter.
Everything happened during that time.
For example, large rats ran around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are meter thick!
The solution is said to have been mixed on eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thank you Demidov!
I guess that's the only reason he hasn't killed anyone with a collapsed ceiling or his own.
Only the building still slowly dies before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house rot, the floors repeatedly collapsed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground like a well.
They say so - under our room a secret laze and a path to the White River, which was specially made by the old believers who once lived here, so that they could hide from danger, in case of what.
They were pursued.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begged to let him start digging in the apartment.
And then he persuaded them to give them a living space in exchange for his one-bedroom apartment on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused to the historian:
Where are the four of us going?
And here at least a tiny hope is that they will give housing more spacious.
If we agreed to an exchange, we wouldn't have won anything.
However, the family of the Elders did not win anything.
Lyudmila’s biggest dream is to be resettled, and her daughter with her 16-year-old granddaughter was given a separate room.
That is, two families have allocated a two-room apartment instead of the most majestic ruins, in which two generations live now.
Cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakov from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two narrow rooms with a total area of 23 m2, called apartments, lives her large family.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see what the conditions are.
Plaster is rolled off in pieces, like window frames, in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms through holes.
The water in the tap all year round is only cold.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house of Ufa, you can see that the most fortunate couple Lavrentiev from apartment No. 4.
They occupy the most spacious rooms on the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room!
The room is 75 squares, three people are registered.
We live just in those rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high, spacious.
One bad thing - everything around breaks at the seams, collapses, collapses.
The neighbors must have already told me.
The most torment we have with the floors: the wooden boards rotted, the earth literally went from under our feet.
I put the supports, wedges; in the hall nothing yet, and in the other room we walk, as on swings swinging, so everything is shaky.
About the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov Alexander Dmitrievich can tell better than any guide.
The goldsmith is treated like a native, speaks about him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kaginsky and Uzyansky plants built houses, cast cannons and bells, held Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they do not want to live under the same roof with history anymore.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around stood wooden rooms for carriages, stables and guard booths, subsequently demolished.
In 1968, they wanted to clean our house, but something prevented it.
The story was repeated in 2014: again beckoned new housing.
We, as a team, collected all the documents, bypassed the necessary authorities, and suddenly found out that the move to apartments is postponed to 2015 or 2016.
I don't believe in all this anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentiev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to learn about the fate of the house.
Officials did not accept the tenant.
They sent from one table to another, and then, as a mockery, issued a paper without a signature and a seal: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of residents."
I even have this feeling that our house has long been absent in terms of the city, because at first it was at number 57, then it became 57 A, and now 57/1.
It's as if it's already been demolished in the '70s.
"Russian Planet" appealed to the head of the sector of information and analytical work of the Department of land resources of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house on the street October Revolution 57/1 is included in the program of resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I cannot be responsible for the actions of the officials of the 70s, only I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite their historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities to restore all the old houses along the street of the October Revolution, representing architectural value, is being successfully implemented.
Residents are planning to move into new apartments soon.
According to Barabash, Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice will restore the Demidov House.
Now in Italy there is an architectural biennale, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016, the entire old Kazanskaya street will be restored, the official says.
Houses will acquire a proper appearance, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
Demidov’s house is likely to become a museum open to all comers.
In addition, at the government level, it was decided to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
On weekdays, unfortunately, it will not work, too much traffic in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to resettle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, they are unlikely to be satisfied: their new apartments will be the same area as the current ones.
Only from another era.
