Eurozone output growth slowed to its lowest in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest value of the Eurozone manufacturing sector’s business activity index (PMI) for Markit fell to 50.7 in August, falling from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates growth.
New orders have been delayed and businesses have suffered amid growing tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures came ahead of a meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will be waiting for a clear plan from the bank on how to cope with the stop of the eurozone recovery, as well as the threat of deflation with inflation of only 0.3%.
There is speculation that ECB chief Mario Draghi may give additional signals later this week that he is considering a quantitative easing scheme for the eurozone similar to those used by Britain and the US during the financial crisis.
“While some growth is better than no growth at all, the inhibitory effect of growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty on producers is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, Markit’s senior economist.
Germany’s manufacturing PMI, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest in 11 months at 51.4.
Meanwhile, in the bloc’s second-largest economy, France, PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to cause real concern, as does Italy’s weakening from stable growth to stagnation.
The signs that the momentum of growth has stalled in the main industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also do not add confidence,” Mr Dobson said.
The slowdown in industry is likely to fuel analysts waiting for additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news was from Ireland, where the PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since late 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August survey of the Eurozone manufacturing sector’s business activity index is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “Eurozone producers are obviously finding life very difficult at the moment, as the current heightened geopolitical tensions – particularly linked to Russia/Ukraine – are adding uncertainty to the still-difficult conditions in many countries.
This increased tension has obviously hit business – and especially consumer confidence – and is likely leading to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
