For most cancers, it is difficult to know the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, the reason is contact with asbestos, a fibrous building material that was once called a “miracle” but which is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is a material from the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when the recommended industrial ban took effect.
Even when it was used, only people from specific industries worked closely with it: pipe-insulators, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it is hardly a cause for concern today.
But such calmness is wrong.
The UK is at the peak of the Mesothelioma epidemic.
More people die from mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death rate of about 2,500 people, more than twice as many people die from the disease than from car accidents.
