The Ministry of Economic Development wants to accelerate the growth of the electric vehicle market
This week, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit to the government a comprehensive plan for the development of environmentally friendly transport in Russia, Deputy Director of the Department Oleg Pluzhnikov said at a round table held by Vedomosti at the Moscow Motor Show - 2014.
The plan was drawn up on behalf of the government, one of the main goals is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
It is expected that the document will be adopted in late September - early October, Pluzhnikov says, the proposed measures relate to electric vehicles and hybrids - a plan for the development of vehicles powered by gas-engine fuel in Russia already exists.
The plan (a copy of "Vedomosti") is designed for 2014-2017.
Criteria for evaluating electric and hybrid transport are to be developed and how to stimulate the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
The report to the government, which will describe tax and customs measures to support electric transport, will be prepared by December 2014; the scheme of preferential lending and preferential leasing will appear by April 2015; and proposals to reduce the price of cars, stimulate localization and create a service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015, it is planned to amend regulations to facilitate the conditions for the construction of charging infrastructure (in parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend to formulate proposals for regional authorities during 2015 that they also encourage the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of giving it an advantage when driving and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such transport.
Finally, by October 2014, the Ministry of Economic Development will include in the list of indicators for assessing the activities of regional authorities criteria that reflect the effectiveness of support for the production of environmentally friendly transport, the development of charging infrastructure.
The market of electric vehicles in Russia is still being formed - in 2013 about 100 electric vehicles were sold in the whole country.
In early 2014, zero import duty on electric cars, so sales will be about 500 pieces, predicts the chief executive of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia Andrey Pankov.
But the five-fold increase does not make electric cars in any way noticeable: in 2013, according to the Association of European Businesses, 2.78 million cars and light commercial vehicles were sold in Russia.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric cars to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start importing - the company focuses primarily on corporate customers, says Nicolas Remiz, Renault's Director of Strategic Planning and Partnerships in Russia.
Most of the other manufacturers of electric transport took a wait-and-see position towards Russia.
The development of electric vehicles has Russian manufacturers — "" GAS, "" but the output is meager.
For example, in January - July 2014, according to ASM-holding, AvtoVAZ produced 30 electric vehicles.
The demand is low due to the high cost of electric vehicles, admits the director of AvtoVAZ Engineering Sergey Amanov, without state support, there will be no breakthrough in this segment.
The development of the Russian market of electric cars in addition to the high cost of cars (those electric cars sold in Russia, on average, twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) restrains the underdevelopment of charging infrastructure (refueling stations - units), sighs the CEO of "Avtostat" Sergey Tselikov.
Due to the high cost and low pace of reducing the cost of electric cars in the next 3-4 years will remain a niche segment of the Russian market, predicts the editor-in-chief of "Avtorev" Mikhail Podorozhansky, Tselikov agrees with him.
Automakers, by contrast, say that some models of electric vehicles are already close to the cost of conventional ones.
The Russian market of electric vehicles has good prospects, the main thing is to inspire confidence in consumers that “electromobility” is real; this, in particular, will contribute to the emergence of new charging stations, emphasizes the President of the BMW Group in Russia Wolfgang Schlimme.
Such infrastructure projects are implemented, for example, by the state-owned company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of gas stations are underway with other regions.
According to Vladimir Sofyin, director of the Rosseti department, the company believes in the electric vehicle market and is ready to build gas stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric vehicles in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric vehicles of various brands.
In addition, Rosseti, as a network company, does not have the right to sell electricity, the possibility of doing this in relation to charging electric vehicles is being worked out.
Pankov believes that the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the electric vehicle market in Russia is the zeroing of customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension, expansion of the preferential list is being worked out.
Replacing the transport tax with an environmental tax (the idea is discussed and applies to all machines) will also support the market, but not as tangible as customs preferences, Pankov believes.
The transport tax in Russia is small, Pankov says, in contrast to Norway, where the tax cut has led to a sharp increase in sales of electric vehicles — now they account for 12% of the market.
In Russia, incentives are also needed for car owners, for example, free parking in the city center (as they have already done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the possibility of moving electric cars on dedicated lanes, which is not yet available in Russia.
