The car recycling program resumed from September 1
From September 1, Russia will resume the program for the disposal of cars.
Until December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As explained by the head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov, the money is allocated from the limits that have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation by redistribution from other areas of support.
The program will apply to all vehicles over the age of six.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a passenger car to 350 thousand rubles for a cargo.
In Russia, a similar program of recycling cars has already been in place.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is assumed not only to dispose of cars for a subsequent discount, but also the possibility, if the car has reached the age of more than six years, to buy a new one at a discount when handing over the old one to a "trade-in" from the dealer.
More than 16 billion rubles were spent on the previous federal recycling program, which was in effect from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011.
Thanks to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 was about 1.2 million units (plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
The creator of Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nikki Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case started working on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact has become widely known only now.
The inspiration for the game came from events in Ferguson, where there are now protests that began after a police officer killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a name, will be how the information coverage of stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a civilian journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in areas where there are clashes between the police and the population.
The hero can take a different picture of what is happening, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene so that the police look like heroes and the protesters like bandits, the police will treat him better and let him go where an ordinary person can not go.
If he covers events differently, his photos could turn peaceful protests into a large-scale riot.
Points in the game will need to be scored with the help of Twitter hero, in which new subscribers will appear, if the photos posted there will be popular.
The game has no name yet.
The release date and the platform on which it will appear are unknown.
Case, however, published an image showing how the event could change depending on how the photo was taken and processed.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been thinking about the concept of such a game for a long time, but initially wanted to devote it not to protests in the United States, but to events in the Gaza Strip.
After he started collecting material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to cover the history of the region.
However, when he saw how the media covered the events in Ferguson, he decided to make a game based on what happened.
Nikki Case is an independent developer who produces browser games.
His most famous project was Coming Out Simulator, released in 2014.
This game, which tells about the events from the biography of Case himself, is devoted to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell about his relationships to homophobic parents.
