The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayuth (right) appointed Minister of Defence Pravitt Wongsuwan (left)
The military ruler and prime minister of Thailand, General Prayuth Chan-ocha, announced the composition of the country's new cabinet, in which more than a third of the posts are held by retired generals or generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: ministers of defense, finance, foreign affairs and trade.
On Monday, Prayuth Chan-ocha was formally confirmed as prime minister after the King of Thailand formally approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old military man who seized power in a bloodless coup on May 22 was the only candidate for prime minister.
He was elected Prime Minister at a session of Parliament.
The army has previously appointed members of parliament.
According to Prayuth Chan-ocha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
It was preceded by six months of demonstrations, during which protesters demanded the resignation of the government of Prime Minister Yingluck Chinawat.
Officially, Prayut Chan-ocha will be the interim prime minister as the military plans to hold a general election in late 2015.
However, there are fears that the military is trying to consolidate its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22
against the background of complete paralysis of civil power.
The leaders of the main political parties were provisionally arrested.
Immediately after the military came to power, they temporarily arrested the country’s leading politicians, including Prime Minister Yinglik Chinawat.
Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis is rooted in 2006, when the army ousted Brother Yinglyk Chinawat Taksin as prime minister.
Both of them are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern regions of the country, which has repeatedly ensured their success in the elections.
However, many representatives of the middle class and the metropolitan elite have joined the anti-government movement, which has practically paralyzed the country since November 2013.
