Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed.
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (SMT), a group of inherited disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that a misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with SMT because so little is known about the condition.
About 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have SMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait and pinched toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and would die before she was 30.
The mother of two, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release an Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical record when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where it shouldn’t, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library, and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that interval.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up and hugged me and said, “My dear, I don’t think you have this disease because you’d already be in a wheelchair.”
I think you've got something that's a lot less life-threatening.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have SMT.
“When he explained what a SMT was, I thought I drew a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK’s SMT charity has announced a month of information on SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The Tax Burden on Washington Zone Entrepreneurs Rises as the Economy Recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose modestly last year as economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to the state treasury and locally in fiscal 2013, a 3.8 percent increase over the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses increased 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when accounts declined, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings in the least amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, tax revenue growth is driven by a return to the previous level of real estate value for companies, the researchers said, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row when growth was less than 1 percent.
While large states such as California, New York and Texas account for a large share of this revenue, it appears that the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 — a 4.2 percent increase from the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate value does not have any similar effect on state and local tax revenue growth in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies’ tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned by either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs’ incomes also appear to be on the mend, according to these figures.
Companies in the region declared a state-wide corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has amassed $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although the trends are directed in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax rate in three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just as it did in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could raise the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to as high as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to feel better and thus pay more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners – the transitional structure under which most small firms are structured – in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, at a much faster rate than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues at state and local levels up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
