Deputies proposed to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, these Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma introduced a draft law that provides for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is located in the legislative base of the lower house.
Its authors were deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Fair Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to faster and more effective protection of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the safety of personal data and compliance with the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is hastened by parliamentarians, obliges to store in the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, clarify and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of the so-called "black lists" of sites-violators - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the CPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay for rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own personal data stores of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom," which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, from the Mail Group, from Western companies that already provide their servers today.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers that are ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
“If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see any problems – they will receive technological opportunities for placement,” Levin said.
Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is adopted, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services of air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be the creation of a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, the systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose in which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the disappearance of global services and significant economic losses.
