Smart Ways to Save Money on University Textbooks
With the cost of university textbooks for many students exceeding $1,000 a year, Matt Schroeder, who will soon be moving into his second year, has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He developed a system of how to rent books from high school students, offering them nominal compensation so that they would postpone their sale.
“My math analysis textbook, which usually costs $180, I got for a semester for $10 and a Chick-fil-A cookie,” says Schroeder, 19, who is studying at Covenant College in Georgia.
The required literature for last semester would have cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
According to the Council of Colleges, the average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and school supplies, but students have a number of options for reducing these costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online stores and creative ideas like the Schroeder system.
Book rentals are becoming increasingly popular, allowing students to use the book during the semester, and often cost significantly less than their purchase.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, says book rentals have doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores were rented out during last spring’s semester, says Trevor Meyer, Nibo’s vice president.
Less than half of all books are purchased from university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here is an introductory course on the best ways to make a profitable deal.
Purchase in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book may be one-third of what you see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of The Mathematical Analysis by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $290 at the price list, but a new copy can be purchased for $239.99 on the website Chegg.com, which specializes in selling textbooks.
Purchase of used
If you don’t mind other people’s notes or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
"Mathematical Analysis" sells for $93.49 in secondhand form on Chegg.com.
Matt Cassady, 25, a fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a second-hand copy of the textbook “Strategic Solutions in Media: Understanding the Business Side of the Advertising Business.”
The book sold for $48.
Teachers, such as Ingrid Bracey, director of the College without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Emherst, are asking students to check with their professors to see if they can use previous publications.
Sometimes updates are not essential for classes.
In such cases, old editions can often be found for a very small fraction of the value of the last edition.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative to buying second-hand books.
Renting
It is worth thinking about renting textbooks if you treat them well enough, do not forget to return them and do not want to keep them after the course is completed.
You can save more than 80% of the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent “Mathematical Analysis” for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the store where you pick up the books, including any fines you may be charged for notes, underscores, and damages.
If you are renting a book, remember that if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented, acquiring an electronic license for a certain period of time from distributors, for example, Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
“Mathematical Analysis” on Chegg.com for six months will cost about $61.
Bracey says that students studying literature can often find the best prices, as many classic works can now be downloaded for free, while literature in the natural and engineering sciences can be very expensive.
No matter what, take a look.
Joe Galt, 29, who is about to start his studies at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using an ISBN to find out the price of a book, as this ensures that you are looking for the text you need.
Before ordering online, says Golt, be sure to check if the book is actually in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
The delivery of the book he had purchased was delayed by four weeks, and he eventually paid the full price at the university bookstore.
