The savings certificate will be made nameless and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates for bearer, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban savings certificates for bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, since the rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since it is not necessary to make deductions to the fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow will suffer from it, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the profile market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASA, is that the customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his licenses are trying to get money in the ASA.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates on bearer, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in case of withdrawal of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the agency's practice, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," the agency said.
The problem is, of course, fictitious.
After all, no one will pay buyers of certificates anyway, since they do not have the right to compensation from the state by law.
If the case was that the instrument is not insured in the ACS, along with it would be prohibited and metal accounts, on which the funds of citizens are accounted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one is trying to exist yet.
The fact is most likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-denomination.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing out such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill stipulates that the savings certificate must be a name security, which must be stored in the depository.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right to early repayment.
That is, an analogue of the irrevocable contribution is introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
