TFR stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 crash in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
The forensic examination showed that the cause of the crash was the increased speed of approach to the landing, the failure of the crew to comply with standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintentional output of the engines to increased direct thrust.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline, which was on the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 during landing at the Moscow Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled over the runway and caught fire.
At the scene, the commander of the aircraft, the co-pilot and the flight engineer were killed.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they later died from their injuries.
Three other flight attendants, hospitalized with serious injuries, were undergoing long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, moving at the time of the crash on the Kiev highway, was seriously injured.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor’s office after the disaster conducted an inspection in the Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
