Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional human emotion
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for mankind, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States found.
About their discoveries, they told in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release of the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - shifted and lowered eyebrows, stretched in a thin line of lips, bloated nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and makes it even blind from birth children who have never seen it, notes the study's lead author Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion arose for the effective conduct of disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his conditions, and he conveys this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmation of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and go to the handicraft, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions unfavorable for them to others, and also prefer forceful methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Starting from the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining”, the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups, creating an angry expression of the face, should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus force as soon as possible to agree to his conditions in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated faces on a computer where each of the seven elements of an angry face was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or forward chin separately did not make the face angry, the physically stronger person depicted with such features, the study participants unanimously recognized.
Man’s anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of his own strength, forcing him to agree and obey.
A person inflates his nostrils and squeezes his lips with the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that demonstrates its fangs.
Anger is “triggered” by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite party the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tubby.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradio company "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft government resolution prepared by the agency, with which Lenta.ru became acquainted.
According to the explanatory note to the draft, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment."
In particular, for the allocated money it is planned to convert the hardware-studio block, video walls, central hardware and video server.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state television and radio broadcasting company “Crimea” was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the TV and radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Teleradio Company "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
